## Summary

Implemented **Bringr-93j.16** — the launch-time Accessibility permission re-grant modal, ported from ClipSlop as a single-permission (Accessibility-only) version.

**New files:**
- `Bringr/PermissionAlertWindow.swift` — floating `NSWindow` subclass (`level = .floating`, transparent titlebar, `isReleasedWhenClosed = false`), hosts the SwiftUI view, with `moveAside()` that slides it to the screen's left edge so it doesn't cover the system prompt.
- `Bringr/PermissionAlertView.swift` — warning header + re-grant explanation, a status card reusing `PermissionStatus` copy, **"Grant Accessibility Access"** (fires `requestAccess()` then slides aside) and **"Open System Settings"** buttons, 4 numbered manual re-grant steps, an optional `@AppStorage("suppressPermissionAlert")` "Don't show this again" toggle (Bringr's first persisted setting, default OFF), and a Close button. Auto-dismisses via `.onChange(of: permissions.isTrusted)`.
- `BringrTests/PermissionAlertTests.swift` — 5 tests over the present/suppress predicate and the shared defaults key.

**Changed:** `AppDelegate` now presents/dismisses the modal (owns the window, gated by `shouldPresentPermissionAlert(isTrusted:suppressed:)` + the suppress default) instead of the bare prompt; `project.pbxproj` wired the three files (IDs 0x35–0x3A).

**Gates:** `** BUILD SUCCEEDED **`, SwiftLint 0 violations, 39 tests pass (5 new).

**Verification:** App launches stably; I confirmed the modal actually appears at launch (this untrusted dev build is the exact target scenario) via `CGWindowListCopyWindowInfo` — 1 Bringr window at layer 3 (`.floating`), 460pt wide. Interactive clicks and live auto-dismiss timing couldn't be exercised headlessly (no display/Screen Recording in this session), but they ride the already-verified `startMonitoring()` path. I documented a reusable headless-window-verification technique in progress.md that will help the upcoming US-006 overlay work.

